nodes.body:
@mattrobball, I'm in the middle of trying to merge `nightly-testing-2024-08-23` here.

I think the merge has caused a bunch of your comments on the PR to become outdated and disappear. Generally, it's better to put such comments in `#adapation_note`s in the actual source code. They are more robust to merging then, and if we can't immediately fix the problems we need these notes in the source code anyway.

Thanks! 

It looks like all my comments are still here but you are of course right.
I highlighted what I view as serious changes/issues.
This highlights one drawback: whenever eta reduction is used, we can now see through it at reducible transparency. So here we simplify to `Membership.mem ..`

(Minor comment, but when leaving comments in huge PRs, it helps if you click and drag through all the changed lines before commenting. This means that the context is visible on the "conversation page", rather than having to wade through the diffs to find the context.)
I'm sorry. I didn't know there was that functionality. Thanks.

I think we can live with this change, and probably we will add eta-reduced lemmas about membership over time. I'm not proposing to do this as part of this PR, but if we add a lemma
```lean
theorem Set.mem_compl_eq {α : Type*} {s : Set α} : (· ∈ sᶜ) = (· ∉ s) := rfl
```
then the proof of `card_fixed_points` is just
```lean
  simp [Set.mem_compl_eq, card_congr (fixedPointsEquiv α), card_perm, Finset.filter_ne']
```
That's a good catch.
With more robust keys, you need to adjust simp theorems. This usually means writing duplicates with the correct types for things.
This seems fine to me, I don't think we need an adaptation note for this.
And you need to copy existing instances with the correct types to get keys that match goal states with those types.
I have added an adaptation note for this, though we might be able to live with it.
I think this is what is envisioned with the design of Lean 4, using `inferInstanceAs`. So I agree.
There is some strain on the elaborator but it is fairly minor.
I think we can live with this, I don't think we need an adaptation note.

All through Lie algebras and with `ChartedSpace` instances on subsets of manifolds. I tried redeclaring these instances to get them to fire but could not figure out the problem. Any help would be appreciated.
I have added an adaptation note for this.
When I get some more time, I will investigate this further to remove the adaptation note. This is really the only serious black mark in the changes.
`convert` can now go deeper via eta reduction
This also seems fine to me.

This is more amusing than problematic in my mind. Since we swap the order into `mem`, the reading of the variables from the notation is reversed from how Lean sees them and `calc` relies on this to work in its current direction when using membership. I think its better than the status quo because 
- you can use subset instead of superset 
- it promotes complex -> simpler terms as a pattern

```suggestion
```

```suggestion
    exact FractionalIdeal.mul_mem_mul (FractionalIdeal.mem_spanSingleton_self _ _) hv
```
